Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 is stable at 212. This includes 19 countries (including 4 territories) from the Western Pacific region, 60 countries (including 7 territories) from the European region, 10 countries from the Southeast Asia region, 22 countries (including 1 territory) from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 54 countries (including 19 territories) from the Americas region, and 47 countries (including 2 territories) from the African region.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:
The Americas region reported 32 111 new cases (43.6% of the global newly reported cases) and 3038 deaths (45.4% of the global newly reported deaths). Of the newly confirmed cases in the region, 74.8% were reported by the USA, followed by Brazil at 7.8% and Canada at 4.8%. Recognizing the USA data are overshadowing the regional proportions, without including the reported newly confirmed cases from the USA, Brazil reported 30.9% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Canada at 19.1%, Peru at 18.7% and Mexico at 9.0%..

The European region reported 31 972 new cases (43.4% of the global newly reported cases) and 3383 deaths (50.6% of the global newly reported deaths). Russia reported 14.9% of the newly confirmed cases in the region, the UK 13.9%, Spain 13.2%, Italy 10.5%, and Turkey 9.6%.

The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 5101 new cases (6.9% of the global newly reported cases) and 143 deaths (2.1% of the global newly reported deaths). Iran reported 1194 new cases representing 23.4% of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Saudi Arabia at 22.3%, Pakistan at 15.0%, Qatar 11.9%, and the United Arab Emirates at 9.5%.

The African region reported 714 new cases (0.97% of the global newly reported cases) and 28 deaths (0.42% of the global newly reported deaths). there were 20 countries reporting no cases in this 24 hour period. That being said, South Africa reported 23.8%% of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Ghana at 15.7%, Algeria at 13.9%, and Guinea at 10.2%.

The Western Pacific region reported 1632 new cases (2.2% of the global newly reported cases) and 25 deaths (0.37% of the global newly reported deaths). Singapore reported 62.3% of the newly reported cases, followed by Japan at 25.9%, and the Philippines at 6.8%. Given the high proportion of cases reported by Singapore, removing Singapore from the denominator, Japan represents 68.7% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by the Philippines at 18.0, and Malaysia at 8.1%.

The South East Asia region reported 2127 new cases (2.9% of the global newly reported cases) and 71 deaths (1.1% of the global newly reported deaths). India reported 66.2% of newly reported cases, followed by Bangladesh at 18.3% and Indonesia at 13.3%. Removing India from the denominator, Bangladesh represents 54.3% of the newly reported cases, Indonesia represents 39.4%, Sri Lanka 2.8%, and Thailand 1.8%.

Figure 4. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region through (23 Apr 2020]) at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the epidemic starting in the Western Pacific, transitioning to multiregional activity as the virus travelled. One sees the contribution of the ongoing epidemics in Europe and now the increasing cases in the Americas region, fueled by the USA, but other countries are following suit. The curve tends to drop over the weekends and rebounds following the weekend the European region increased following the weekend but to lower levels than the prior week. The America's region does not appear to have decreased. One sees a gradual increase in the number of cases from the Africa Region. One wonders if the cases globally may have peaked near 6 Apr 2020. Time will tell.

A somewhat repetitive but necessary reminder: It is clear that the number of reported confirmed cases differs from different reporting websites and is somewhat a function of time of day the website is updated. For example, I note the time we've accessed the Johns Hopkin's CSSE or Worldometer website, but by the time the post is actually finished with the editing process, those numbers have at times significantly changed. Case counting is clearly a moving target, and depending upon when the website updates, the numbers may be different. I try to start each post with the latest figures for the calendar day (the John Hopkins CSSE or Worldometer table) and close with the figures from the start of the calendar day (the WHO tables), defining the calendar day as DST (now GMT-4). - Mod.MPP]
